Welcome to Police Watch! We offer an exclusive and authentic look into the world of law enforcement through the lens of body-worn cameras. Our channel provides raw and unfiltered footage of police officers in action, from routine traffic stops to high-stakes situations.

Our police body camera channel is filled with a range of topics that will pique your interest, including transparency, accountability, community engagement, trust-building, law enforcement procedures, officer safety, de-escalation tactics, civil rights, and more.

We understand the importance of building trust between law enforcement and the communities they serve, and we believe that our channel plays a role in fostering that relationship. By sharing body camera footage, we offer viewers an unprecedented look into the realities of police work and the challenges that officers face on a daily basis.

Cats of San Bernardino was started by Jaina and Ivy Spagis when they moved to San Bernardino in 2016
from Los Angeles. They were shocked that San Bernardino did not offer free spay and neuter
services like LA and realized that the feral situation in their new neighborhood was out of
control. They began trapping and spaying/neutering feral cats at their own expense, but soon
realized the problem was too big to tackle on their own.

They have converted their home into an animal sanctuary, providing space for kittens and their
mommas waiting for adoption, rehabilitation areas for recovering injured cats, play areas for
healthy cats. With the help of foster families in the city of San
Bernardino they have as many as 50 cats in their care at one time.Their dream is to one day
have a large property/facility which will help save thousands of more lives. This new property
would have catios, feral enclosures, a medical room, nursery, rehabilitation area, and adoption
center.

Before television, people came to movie theatres to watch the news. British Path√© was at the forefront of cinematic journalism, blending information with entertainment to popular effect. Over the course of a century, it documented everything from major armed conflicts and seismic political crises to the curious hobbies and eccentric lives of ordinary people. If it happened, British Path√© filmed it.

Now considered to be the finest newsreel archive in the world, British Path√© is a treasure trove of 85,000 films unrivalled in their historical and cultural significance.

British Path√© also represents the Reuters historical collection, which includes more than 136,000 items from the news agencies Gaumont Graphic (1910-1932), Empire News Bulletin (1926-1930), British Paramount (1931-1957), and Gaumont British (1934-1959), as well as Visnews content from 1957 to the end of 1984. All footage can be viewed on the British Path√© website. www.britishpathe.com

description:
Welcome to the world of Taarak Mehta Ka Ooltah Chashmah Hindi Rhymes! This collection of entertaining and educational rhymes will introduce your child to the vibrant Hindi language and culture. Our rhymes are based on the lovable characters such as Tapu Sena, Jethalal, Daya, Babita, Popatlal of popular Indian sitcom, Taarak Mehta Ka Ooltah Chashmah, making it a fun and engaging experience for kids.

Our TMKOC videos combine colorful animation, catchy tunes, and easy-to-follow lyrics to create a joyful and interactive learning environment. Whether your child is learning hindi for the first time or is a native speaker, our TMKOC rhymes will help them improve their language skills, build vocabulary, and develop a love for Hindi.

So, come and join Jethalal, Daya Ben, and the rest of the gang as we sing and dance along to the Taarak Mehta Ka Ooltah Chashmah Rhymes. With new rhymes added regularly, your child will never run out of opportunities to learn and have fun!

Welcome to the world of Taarak Mehta Ka Ooltah Chashmah Marathi Rhymes! This collection of entertaining and educational rhymes will introduce your child to the vibrant Marathi language and culture. Our videos combine colorful animation, catchy tunes, and easy-to-follow lyrics to create a joyful and interactive learning environment. Whether your child is learning Marathi for the first time or is a native speaker, our rhymes will help them improve their language skills, build vocabulary, and develop a love for Marathi.

So, come and join Jethalal, Daya Ben, and the rest of the gang as we sing and dance along to the Taarak Mehta Ka Ooltah Chashmah Marathi Rhymes. With new rhymes added regularly, your child will never run out of opportunities to learn and have fun!

I suspect I am someway along the autism spectrum because I get very focused on a project once I start. I was once described by a colleague as a "finisher" in that I was very driven to finish something once I had started. This is not always a good thing as it can mean pushing on when many others would recognise a lost cause and give up. Nonetheless I enjoy what I do and as a former teacher I recognise the importance of passing on one's knowledge whenever possible. To that end I am happy to post my rather quirky selection of videos. titre: Cut The Camera Podcast (by the sturniolo triplets)
description: Having lived in Boston their whole life and now balancing living in two places at once, the Sturniolo Triplets aren't your everyday siblings. These social media power houses spend most of their lives in front of the camera, making content for the millions of fans who have come to know and love them. But what happens when the cameras are off and they aren't creating content? Well, on the Cut the Camera podcast, Nick, Matt, and Chris are going to give their fans the unfiltered, real to life experience of hanging out with them as they share who they are when no one is watching.  Nick, Matt, and Chris are here to bring you along for the ride as they continue to shape and define who they are and what obstacles they need to overcome as they live a life in the public eye. From mental health, questions & theories to special guests, this podcast is here to give you even more of what you already know and love from the Sturniolo Triplets. So follow along as we Cut the Camera.

After doing holiday jobs on a few farms, I knew this was what I really wanted to do. After 4-years of study at Shuttleworth Agricultural Collage in 1980, I left with an HND and a job as a on-farm grain-buyer in the Beds and Bucks area with a company called Grainec. 
I loved this job but I still wanted to be a proper farmer one day, so started taking on small parcels of grassland and buying ewes with lambs at foot to fatten up. I soon discovered sheep farming was too time consuming to keep the day job so turned my attention to taking on arable land, using contractors to work the land to allow me to expand quicker. 
I'd noticed a few of the farmers I was dealing with felt trapped on their farms because it was impossible for them to take time off, so I offered to take the land on for a year to give them a break. The first farm I took on was 242ac in 1985, by 1990, this has grown to over 1000ac. Evo came along in 1998 after a lucky break and the farming(now 2000ac) had to take a back seat
